<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Alumina Hydrate" class="currentChild" href="Alumina_Hydrate">Alumina Hydrate</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A white, inorganic compound used as a <a title="white pigment" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/white_pigment">white pigment</a> in printing inks. Alumina hydrate (chemical composition Al<sub>2</sub>O3.O-3SO3.3H<sub>2</sub>O) is mined from bauxite, is highly transparent, and is used as an <a title="Extender" href="Extender">extender</a> pigment in lithographic and screen printing inks. It is chemically resistant to most substances, with the exception of dilute hydrochloric acid. It also improves the flow of <a title="lithographic" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/lithographic">lithographic</a> inks and the <a title="Gloss" href="Gloss">gloss</a> of a variety of other types of inks. (See also <a title="White Pigments" href="White_Pigments">White Pigments</a>.) 
</p>
<p id="l3">
Also known as <a title="Light Alumina Hydrate" href="Light_Alumina_Hydrate">Light Alumina Hydrate</a>, <a title="Lake White" href="Lake_White">Lake White</a>, and <a title="Transparent White" href="Transparent_White">Transparent White</a> ('CI Pigment White 24 No. 77002'). 
</p>
